			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Is anyone Playing EQ2?<a name="74187"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 9 05 10:15 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I made the switch to EQ2 along with my regular group. I also cancelled my EQ1 subscription. My experience of EQ2 so far has been that it simply was not ready for release at the launch date. I estimate they still had 3-6 months of work, but the WoW launch date forced them into bringing it out early.
<br />

<br />
As far as the game itself goes it reminds me alot of DAoC, from which they borrowed alot of their concepts. The game does have a large amount of potential, and I am confident SOE will get things ironed out over time. It also boasts the best tradeskill system in any MMORPG to date bar none.
<br />

<br />
However, it is not the next-generation step up that has been suggested. Mobs still act as dumbly as in EQ1, and anti-kiting code has replaced summoning as the crutch for this. Until the AI improves I don't think you can describe any game as a generation above EQ and DAoC.
<br />

<br />
In short, if you are bored by EQ1, then EQ2 (and WoW) might be a good game to try out. If not then you could do worse than holding off for 3 months or so until they get more of the issues resolved. If you are simply looking for an online 'bridge' game between EQ1 and your chosen game from the upcoming releases then look at Guild Wars since it has no monthly fee and follows the CoH model of 'pick up and play'.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
